   "source": [
    "import jax.numpy as jnp\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from jax import lax\n",
    "\n",
    "from pyhgf.model import Network\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"figure.constrained_layout.use\"] = True\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(43)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When using value coupling in previous examples, the coupling function $g$ between nodes was assumed to be linear (in the form of $g(x) = Ax + B$). This assumes linear influence of the belief parent. Since both the belief update step and the prediction step use either the first and second-order derivatives of the coupling function $g'$ and $g''$ or the function itself, in the case of a linear coupling the equations for prediction and updates of continuous state nodes can be simplified, as $x$ disappears during the derivation process.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, different coupling functions between value parents and children could be used to model different kinds of stochastic processes. In PyHGF, if coupling functions between nodes are not specified, the default equations are the simplified ones (in which the coupling function is assumed to be the identity function), but it is possible to manually input any other functions in the parent node when building the network, as long as it is two times differentiable in JAX. In this notebook, we illustrate how to do it and provide some relevant examples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For this tutorial, we will try to fit a 2-level continuous HGF to some data that are expected to behave in a known non-linear way. Let's consider a signal $u_1$ consisting of a Gaussian random walk with some drift."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {

   "source": [
    "# create u as a Gaussian random walk\n",
    "low_noise = 0.5\n",
    "u_1 = np.cumsum(np.random.normal(0.03, 0.5, 1000)) + np.random.normal(\n",
    "    0.01, low_noise, 1000\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# plot the signal\n",
    "_, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "ax.plot(u_1, marker=\".\", alpha=0.5, linestyle=\"\")\n",
    "ax.set(xlabel=r\"$x$\", ylabel=r\"$f(x)$\", title=r\"Gaussian random walk, $u$\")\n",
    "ax.grid(linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "sns.despine()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Imagine that this behaviour constitutes a signal of a given underlying phenomenon. Now, we want to measure the same phenomenon with another instrument that above an arbitrary threshold $a$ can track the signal $u_2$, but below that threshold just gives us some noise. This measurement $u_1$ is supposed to be also noisier than the underlying signal."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.503047Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.502831Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.684806Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.683671Z"
    },
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": [
     "hide-input"
    ]
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "high_noise = 5\n",
    "a = 20  # setting an arbitrary threshold\n",
    "u2 = u_1 - (u_1 * (u_1 < a).astype(int)) + (np.random.normal(0, high_noise, 1000))\n",
    "\n",
    "# plot the signal\n",
    "_, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))\n",
    "ax.plot(u2, marker=\".\", alpha=0.5, linestyle=\"\")\n",
    "ax.set(xlabel=r\"$x$\", ylabel=r\"$f(x)$\", title=r\"Noisy signal, $u_2$\")\n",
    "ax.grid(linestyle=\"--\")\n",
    "sns.despine()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The [ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rectifier_(neural_networks)) is commonly used in artificial neural networks and is defined as the non-negative part of its argument:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "f(x) = \n",
    "\\begin{cases} \n",
    "\\ x & \\text{for } x > 0 \\\\\n",
    " 0 & \\text{for } x \\leq 0 \n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "```{figure} https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/42/ReLU_and_GELU.svg\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "If we know the underlying dynamic of the original signal ($u_2$), can we build an HGF network capable of using this information to predict the behaviour of the measured signal ($u_1$)?\n",
    "\n",
    "Yes, through non-linear coupling! \n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine a network in which a value parent node $x_2$ receives information both from a continuous input node registering $u_2$ and a child node $x_1$ connected to another continuous input node registering $u_1$. Then we can calculate $x_2$ and $x_1$ as follows.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "x_2^{(k)} \\sim Normal(\\lambda_2x_2^{(k-1)}, \\theta_2)\\\\\n",
    "x_1^{(k)} \\sim Normal(g_{2,1}(x_2^{(k)})), \\theta_1)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\lambda$ is the autoconnection strength and $\\theta$ the tonic volatility of each node. Note that the autoconnection strength of $x_1$ is set to 0, so that the node mean is informed just by $g_{2,1}(x_2^{(k)})$, being $g_{2,1}$ the coupling function between $x_2$ and $x_1$. This allows us to couple the two nodes without $x_1^{(k)}$ being influenced by its previous state.\n",
    "\n",
    "We now create first a network structure with all linear couplings ($g_{2,1}$ is the identity function), and then the same structure with a non-linear coupling."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

       "</g>\n",
       "<!-- x_3 -->\n",
       "<g id=\"node4\" class=\"node\">\n",
       "<title>x_3</title>\n",
       "<ellipse fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\" cx=\"45\" cy=\"-162\" rx=\"18\" ry=\"18\"/>\n",
       "<text text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"45\" y=\"-158.3\" font-family=\"Times,serif\" font-size=\"14.00\">3</text>\n",
       "</g>\n",
       "<!-- x_3&#45;&gt;x_1 -->\n",
       "<g id=\"edge2\" class=\"edge\">\n",
       "<title>x_3&#45;&gt;x_1</title>\n",
       "<path fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\" d=\"M38.74,-144.76C35.5,-136.37 31.47,-125.93 27.83,-116.5\"/>\n",
       "<polygon fill=\"black\" stroke=\"black\" points=\"31.09,-115.22 24.23,-107.15 24.56,-117.74 31.09,-115.22\"/>\n",
       "</g>\n",

       "<g id=\"edge3\" class=\"edge\">\n",

       "<path fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\" d=\"M51.26,-144.76C54.5,-136.37 58.53,-125.93 62.17,-116.5\"/>\n",
       "<polygon fill=\"black\" stroke=\"black\" points=\"65.44,-117.74 65.77,-107.15 58.91,-115.22 65.44,-117.74\"/>\n",
       "</g>\n",
       "</g>\n",
       "</svg>\n"
      ],

     "execution_count": 5,

   ],
   "source": [
    "linear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=1 / high_noise**2)  # u1 - Continuous node 0\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=1 / (low_noise) ** 2)  # u2 - Continuous node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, n_nodes=1, autoconnection_strength=0)  # x1 - node 2\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=[1, 2],\n",
    "        n_nodes=1,\n",
    "    )  # x2 - node 3\n",
    ")\n",
    "linear_hgf.plot_network()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to implement the non-linear coupling, we need to specify a coupling function $g_{2,1}$. In this case, we need a function that allows $x_1$ to predict that the input signal below a threshold will be just random noise, but above the threshold is equal to the behaviour displayed by $u_2$.\n",
    "\n",
    "We can therefore shape the function as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{cases} \n",
    "\\ u_2 & \\text{for } x > a \\\\\n",
    " 0 & \\text{for } x \\leq a \n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For now, we are fixing the parameters knowing how the signal is generated.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.717770Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.717423Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.721048Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.720170Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Creating the functions\n",
    "def g(x, a=20):\n",
    "    return lax.cond(x > a, lambda x: x, lambda x: 0.0, x)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is then possible to input the function into the parent node, using the argument `coupling_fn`, that accepts tuples. \n",
    "When `coupling_fn` is not specified, the coupling is assumed to be linear (identity function) and the argument passes a `None` tuple, where the number of `None` element matches the number of value children.\n",
    "If the value parent, as in this case, possesses multiple children, all the functions must be inputed in the same order the value children are declared in the `value_children` argument. To input an identity function it is possible to write `None`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,

   "source": [
    "nonlinear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=10.0)  # u1 - Continuous node 0\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=10.0)  # u2 - Continuous node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, n_nodes=1, autoconnection_strength=0)  # x1 - node 2\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=[1, 2], n_nodes=1, coupling_fn=(None, g)\n",
    "    )  # x2 - node 3 - coupling functions expressed\n",
    ")\n",
    "nonlinear_hgf.plot_network()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's see how our two networks perform when we input the data."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.743604Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.743429Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.746563Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:48.745686Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# data input\n",
    "input_data = input_data = np.array([u_1, u2]).T"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice how the HGF manages to track the gaussian random walk even with the linear coupling. However, it is using data coming from $u_2$ to inform $x_1$ state through the value parent $x_2$ even below the threshold, something that in this specific example is incorrect, as $u_1$ behaviour is non-linear and depends on a threshold. Providing a coupling function allows us to use the information coming from $u_2$ just when needed, allowing a more precise tracking."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Non-linear predictions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Non-linear coupling functions can be used also to build networks able to track in real time the oscillation frequency of sinusoidal waves.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's simulate an oscillatory signal with some noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:53.063161Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:53.062978Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:53.067522Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:53.066351Z"
    },
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "x = np.arange(0, 1000)\n",
    "std = 0.1\n",
    "input_data = np.sin(x / 20) + np.random.normal(0, std, 1000)  # sinusoid + noise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "source": [
    "We would like to build a network capable of predicting that the signal is oscillating, even when it is not given new observations. When using a linear HGF, if observations are not given, the update function will continue running setting the prediction error $\\delta$ to zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "This means that the predicted mean ($\\mu_a$) of a node will depend just on its prediction mean ($\\hat{\\mu_a}$), that depends on the degree of autocorrelation and the total predicted drift ($P_a$).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mu_a^{(k)} = \\lambda_a \\cdot \\mu_a^{(k-1)} + P_a\\\\\n",
    "P_a = t^{(k)} \\cdot (\\rho_a + \\alpha_{b,a}g_{b,a}(\\mu_b^{(k-1)}))\n",
    "$$\n",
    "where $t$ is the timestep, $\\alpha$ the coupling strength, and $\\rho$ tonic drift. Notice that the timestep is coded outside the coupling function (this information will come in handy for the non-linear coupling).\n",
    "\n",
    "With a linear coupling the predicted mean will just keep drifting, while the precision will progressively increase, as you can see in this example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {

   "source": [
    "sinusoid_linear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=1 / std**2)  # input\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, n_nodes=1, autoconnection_strength=1)  # x1 - node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=1,\n",
    "        n_nodes=1,\n",
    "    )  # x2 - node 2\n",
    ")\n",
    "sinusoid_linear_hgf.plot_network()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {

    "sinusoid_linear_hgf.plot_trajectories();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.567065Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.566885Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.571452Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.570651Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(0,)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sinusoid_linear_hgf.input_idxs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice how $\\mu_1$ is just drifting during the missing observation chuncks.\n",
    "\n",
    "If we want to implement a non-linear HGF capable of tracking a sinusoidal mean, we can't just update the coupling function using the same structure, as the $g$ appears only in the total predicted drift, and will just vary, at best, the steepness of the drift slope."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.573471Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:54.573296Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.013346Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.012130Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1800x900 with 6 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(precision=1 / std**2)  # input\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, n_nodes=1, autoconnection_strength=1)  # x1 - node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=1, n_nodes=1, coupling_fn=(jnp.sin,))  # x2 - node 2\n",
    ")\n",
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf = sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf.input_data(\n",
    "    input_data, observed=observed\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# plot traces\n",
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf.plot_trajectories();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This happens because time is not included directly inside $g$, a fact that doesn't allow the transformation of all the terms from the native space to the sinusoidal space.\n",
    "A way to overcome this limitation is assuming constant time steps and setting a parent $x_2$ as an \"internal clock\", and adding a drift parent $x_3$ that can learn the oscillation frequency (when the frequency is varying during time).\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mu_3^{(k)} = \\lambda_3 \\cdot \\mu_3^{(k-1)} + t^{(k)} \\cdot (\\rho_3)\\\\\n",
    "\\mu_2^{(k)} = \\lambda_2 \\cdot \\mu_2^{(k-1)} + t^{(k)} \\cdot (\\rho_2 + \\alpha_{3,2}(\\mu_3^{(k-1)}))\\\\\n",
    "\\mu_1^{(k)} =  t^{(k)} \\cdot (\\alpha_{2,1}g_{b,a}(\\mu_2^{(k-1)}))\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "In this way, given $t^{(k)}$ constant, $\\mu_1^{(k)}$ will depend just on $g_{b,a}(\\mu_2^{(k-1)})$. If $\\mu_2$ represents the time passing as a line, steeper slopes will indicate increased frequencies of oscillation. The steepness of the slope can be learnt by the drift parent when the oscillation frequency is variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "To understand the dependency of the oscillating frequency of $x_1$ from the slope of $x_2$, consider having a signal with a fixed frequency.\n",
    "The drift corresponds to the slope of $\\mu_2(t)$, which equals to $1/f$, being $f/2\\pi$ the oscillation frequency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.015501Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.015321Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.020007Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.018911Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        precision=1 / std**2\n",
    "    )  # u1 - Continuous node 0\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, autoconnection_strength=0)  # x1 - node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=1,\n",
    "        tonic_drift=0.05,  # fixed drift\n",
    "        autoconnection_strength=1,\n",
    "        coupling_fn=(jnp.sin,),\n",
    "    )  # x2 - node 2\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.042979Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:56.042731Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.421721Z",

     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1800x900 with 6 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf = sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf.input_data(\n",
    "    input_data, observed=observed\n",
    ")\n",
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf.plot_trajectories();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Frequency tracking"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have shown that a constand drift correspond to a constant oscillation frequency. What if we want our network to learn the oscillation frequency changing over time? We can add a drift parent $x_3$ to inform the slope of $x_2$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.424176Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.423934Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.428548Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.427756Z"
    },
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "x = np.ones(1000)\n",
    "x[400:600] = (\n",
    "    5  # this parameter sets the frequency of the central part of the sinusoid wave\n",
    ")\n",
    "x = np.cumsum(x)\n",
    "std = 0.1\n",
    "\n",
    "input_data = np.sin(x / 20) + np.random.normal(0, std, 1000)  # sinusoid + noise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {
    "editable": true,
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.430672Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.430501Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.434717Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2025-08-23T18:01:57.433933Z"
    },
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": ""
    },
    "tags": []
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sinusoid_nonlinear_hgf = (\n",
    "    Network()\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        precision=1 / std**2\n",
    "    )  # u1 - Continuous node 0\n",
    "    .add_nodes(value_children=0, autoconnection_strength=0)  # x1 - node 1\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=1, mean=0.0, autoconnection_strength=1, coupling_fn=(jnp.sin,)\n",
    "    )  # x2 - node 2\n",
    "    .add_nodes(\n",
    "        value_children=2,\n",
    "        mean=0.0,\n",
    "        precision=10,\n",
    "        tonic_volatility=-8,  # you can change this parameter according to how fast the signal is changing\n",
    "    )  # x3 - node 3\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
